    <h2>&quot;Cookies&quot;</h2>
    <p>When viewing this site or any site linked from this site, we may store some information on your computer in the form of a "cookie". Using this information we can measure site activity and tailor information to suit your individual preferences. Cookies can display the time and duration of the visit, the pages you visit on our sites and the Website that referred you to our website. The goal is to save you time and make the visit more meaningful.</p>

    <p>A cookie is a small text file stored on your computer by the website you're visiting. Cookies are used by many web sites to give visitors access to various functions. The information in the cookie can be used to monitor user behavior on the web. There are two types of cookies. One type of cookie saves a file for a long time on your computer and is used, for example, along with functions which describe what information is new since you last visited that particular page. The second type of cookie, also called "session cookie" temporarily stored in the computer's memory while you are visiting the site. A session cookie could, for example, keep track of what language you have chosen at the website. Session cookies are not stored for any length of time, they disappear when you close your browser. TERESAH use cookies, for example to handle logged in users.</p>

    <p>You can set your computer to block cookies. However, this means that TERESAH can not guarantee that all areas of our website functions as intended. How do you do it to block cookies depends on what browser you use. Learn more about these features in the instructions or help screen to the browser.
